  • No campfires at Thousand Island Lake, Garnet, Ruby, Emerald, Badger or Clark Lakes; and no campfires above 10,000 ft. Map of campfire restrictions are on USFS Webpage

  • No camping within 300 ft. of the outflow of Thousand Island Lake or Garnet Lake

  • Bear containers are required for storage of food and trash

  • Ansel Adams Wilderness regulations apply

  • Yosemite wilderness regulations apply if entering the park (no pets, no bear spray)

All visitors to Reds Meadow Valley pay a transportation fee which allows use of the mandatory shuttle bus. Call Mammoth Lakes Welcome Center for more shuttle information, (760) 924-5500.

USFS Webpage for: River Trail.

https://www.fs.usda.gov/recarea/inyo/recreation/hiking/recarea/?recid=21264

435.name: River Trail

436.description:
Glacier-fed Minaret Lake is at the foot of Minaret pinnacles in the Ritter Range. From Devils Postpile Visitor Center (shuttle stop #6) it is less than a mile to a bridge across the river and the junction with the John Muir Trail.

You follow the John Muir Trail for a short distance as it climbs above Minaret Falls to Johnston Lake where the Minaret Lake trail separates from the John Muir Trail.

This permit does not include the John Muir Trail past Johnson Lake. Follow the trail along Minaret Creek to its source at Minaret Lake.

Download map for trail names in this area.

https://www.fs.usda.gov/Internet/FSE_DOCUMENTS/stelprdb5337628.pdf

description_map.need_to_know:
Minaret Lake Area: 

This permit does not include trips going toward Beck Lake, Fern Lake, or continuing on the John Muir Trail past Johnson Lake.

  • No campfires at Minaret Lakes or Deadhorse Lake and all locations above 10,000 ft. This area has additional campfire restrictions below 10,000ft. Map of campfire restrictions are on USFS Webpage. 
  • Bear containers are required for storage of food and trash. 
  • Ansel Adams Wilderness regulations apply.  

All visitors to Reds Meadow Valley pay a transportation fee which allows use of the mandatory shuttle bus. Call Mammoth Lakes Welcome Center for more shuttle information, (760) 924-5500. 

USFS Webpage for: Minaret Lake. 

https://www.fs.usda.gov/recarea/inyo/recreation/hiking/recarea/?recid=20540

436.name: Minaret Lake

437.description:
Beck Lake trail also goes to some little known places like Noname, Lost Dog, Superior and Holcomb Lakes.

From shuttle stop #6 in front of the Devils Postpile Visitor Center it is less than a mile to the junction where a bridge across the river leads to several trail junctions. Above Minaret Falls you leave the John Muir Trail.

Beck Lake trail does not include trips to Minaret Lake or north on the John Muir Trail.

Download map for trail names in this area.

description_map.need_to_know:
Beck Lake Area:

This permit does not include the John Muir Trail.

  • No campfires at Beck Lakes, Holcomb, Ashley, Anona or Fern Lakes; and no campfires above 10,000 ft., look at USFS Webpage for campfire restriction maps.

  • Bear containers are required for storage of food and trash.

  • There are several different trails in the area. Check the area map to select the correct trail.

  • All visitors to Reds Meadow Valley pay a transportation fee which allows use of the mandatory shuttle bus. Call Mammoth Lakes Welcome Center for more shuttle information (760) 924-5500.

  • Ansel Adams Wilderness regulations apply.

USFS Webpage for: Beck Lake.

437.name: Beck Lake

438.description:
The Fern Lake trail follows Snow Canyon toward King's Creek and Summit Meadow on the way to Fern and Anona Lakes. Start from the Devils Postpile Visitor Center, shuttle stop #6. It is less than a mile to the junction with the John Muir Trail where a bridge across the river leads to several trail junctions. You can continue past Summit Meadow and Granite Stairway to join the Mammoth trail in Sierra National Forest.

Download map for trail names in this area.

Note: Fern Lake permit does not include continuing on the John Muir Trail.

https://www.fs.usda.gov/Internet/FSE_DOCUMENTS/stelprdb5337628.pdf

description_map.need_to_know:
Fern Lake Area:  

Fern Lake permit does not include continuing on the John Muir Trail.

  • No campfires at Fern Lake, Anona, Ashley, Holcomb or Beck Lakes; and no campfires above 10,000 ft. 
  • Bear containers are required for storage of food and trash. 
  • All visitors to Reds Meadow Valley pay a transportation fee which allows use of the mandatory shuttle bus. Call Mammoth Lakes Welcome Center for more shuttle information. (760) 924-5500. 
  • Ansel Adams Wilderness regulations apply.  

USFS Webpage for: Fern Lake. 

https://www.fs.usda.gov/recarea/inyo/recreation/hiking/recarea/?recid=20544

438.name: Fern Lake

439.description:
Starting from Horseshoe Lake in the Mammoth Lakes Basin, this trail goes past McCloud Lake and over the relatively moderate Mammoth Pass. Look for the Red Cones rock feature the trail is named for near Crater Meadow. Several trail junctions offer options to go to Reds Meadow or the John Muir Trail, either north or south. Common destinations are the Fish Creek and Cascade Valley areas.

Check the area map to select the correct trail name. Trips going toward Deer Lakes or Duck Pass are a different reservation.

Download map for trail names in this area.

https://www.fs.usda.gov/Internet/FSE_DOCUMENTS/stelprdb5337629.pdf

description_map.need_to_know:
Red Cones Area: 

Red Cones permit may continue on the John Muir Trail, either north or south.

  • No camping at McCloud Lake 
  • No campfires above 10,000 ft. and no campfires in many specific areas. Map of campfire restrictions are on USFS Webpage 
  • Bear containers are required for storage of food and trash 
  • Ansel Adams and John Muir Wilderness regulations apply 
  • Yosemite, Sequoia and Kings Canyon wilderness regulations apply if entering the National Parks (includes no pets, no bear spray, no night box permit pickup; smaller group size limits off trail).  

USFS Webpage for: Red Cones. 

https://www.fs.usda.gov/recarea/inyo/recreation/hiking/recarea/?recid=20500

439.name: Red Cones

440.description:
Starting from Horseshoe Meadows, Cottonwood Pass trail is the gateway to the northern part of Golden Trout Wilderness and connects to the Pacific Crest Trail near the top of Cottonwood Pass. Small streams meander through tree-rimmed meadows in this wilderness area named for California's state fish, the Golden Trout. Options for loop trips of various lengths branch out from Big Whitney Meadow. Following the Pacific Crest Trail north into Sequoia National Park leads to Crabtree Meadows and the headwaters of the Kern River.

Download map for trail names in this area. This permit does not go to Cottonwood Lakes.

https://www.fs.usda.gov/Internet/FSE_DOCUMENTS/stelprdb5337644.pdf

description_map.need_to_know:
Cottonwood Pass Area:

Cottonwood Pass permit may continue on the PCT/JMT  

  • No campfires at Rocky Basin Lakes or Chicken Spring Lake. 
  • Bear container required area for storage of food and trash. Look at USFS Webpage for map of food storage restriction area. 
  • Cottonwood Pass permit may continue on the Pacific Crest Trail. Check the area map for the correct trail name. Trips going toward Cottonwood Lakes are a different permit. 
  • Golden Trout Wilderness regulations apply. 
  • Sequoia and Kings Canyon wilderness regulations apply if entering the National Park (includes no pets; off trail group size limit eight; three night limit at Soldier Lakes).  

USFS Webpage: Cottonwood Pass. 

https://www.fs.usda.gov/recarea/inyo/recreation/hiking/recarea/?recid=20812

440.name: Cottonwood Pass

441.description:
A steep climb past several cascading waterfalls leads to Lake Helen on the Lundy Canyon Trail. After Lake Helen more moderate terrain is found in the Twenty Lakes Basin. Trails circle toward Saddlebag Lake and to the foot of North Peak and Mount Conness on the Yosemite National Park boundary.

Download map for trail names in this area.

https://www.fs.usda.gov/Internet/FSE_DOCUMENTS/stelprdb5337621.pdf

description_map.need_to_know:
Lundy Canyon Area: 

Lundy Canyon is a non quota trail with unlimited entry to Hoover Wilderness. Book your trip about a week before your entry date to allow time to check in by email.  

  • No campfires in Twenty Lakes Basin or Hall Natural Research Area.
  • Food and refuse must be stored in a container designed to prevent access by bears, or counter-balanced at least 15 feet above the ground and 10 feet horizontally from a tree trunk (where containers are not required). 
  • No camping in Hall Natural Research Area.
  • Guiding in Hoover wilderness is by Yosemite Mountaineering School only. 
  • Hoover Wilderness regulations apply.  

USFS Webpage for: Lundy Canyon. 

https://www.fs.usda.gov/recarea/inyo/recreation/hiking/recarea/?recid=20646

441.name: Lundy Canyon (Non Quota)

442.description:
Starting from Onion Valley, the trail to Golden Trout Lakes is rough and sometimes difficult to follow as it climbs high alpine basins containing the Golden Trout Lakes. This trail does not cross the Sierra Crest. 

Permit for Golden Trout Lakes trail does not include Kearsarge Pass. 

Download map for trail names in this area. 

https://www.fs.usda.gov/Internet/FSE_DOCUMENTS/stelprdb5337642.pdf

description_map.need_to_know:
Golden Trout Lakes Area: 

Special approval is required for commercial use. The trail is not recommended for stock.  

  • Permit for Golden Trout Lakes trail does not include Kearsarge Pass area.
  • Campfires are prohibited. 
  • Food and refuse must be stored in a container designed to prevent access by bears, or counter-balanced at least 15 feet above the ground and 10 feet horizontally from a tree trunk (where containers are not required). 
  • John Muir Wilderness regulations apply.  

USFS Webpage for: Golden Trout Lakes. 

https://www.fs.usda.gov/recarea/inyo/recreation/hiking/recarea/?recid=20778

442.name: Golden Trout Lakes

443.description:
Deer Lakes trail is sometimes called the Crystal Crag trail. This trail begins with a steep climb up the ridge from Lake George to the Mammoth Crest with spectacular views of Crystal Crag and Crystal Lake. The trail continues along the rim of the Sierra Crest with views into the back country toward the Middle Fork of the San Joaquin River. Deer Lake is at the end of the trail.

If you want to connect to the John Muir Trail use the Duck Pass or Red Cones trail.

Download map for trail names in this area.

https://www.fs.usda.gov/Internet/FSE_DOCUMENTS/stelprdb5337629.pdf

description_map.need_to_know:
Deer Lakes Area:

  • No campfires above 10,000 ft.

  • Food and refuse must be stored in a container designed to prevent access by bears, or counter-balanced at least 15 feet above the ground and 10 feet horizontally from a tree trunk (where containers are not required). View food storage restriction area maps. Surrounding areas require use of bear containers.

  • Camping is not allowed at Crystal Lake.

  • Check the area map to select the correct trail name.

  • John Muir Wilderness regulations apply.

USFS Webpage for: Deer Lake.

https://www.fs.usda.gov/recarea/inyo/recreation/hiking/recarea/?recid=20498

443.name: Deer Lakes

444.description:
Climbing over Duck Pass to join the John Muir trail, the Duck Pass trail climbs the forested hillside behind Coldwater Campground and goes past Arrowhead, Skelton, and Barney Lakes before going over Duck Pass. A side trail to Emerald Lake offers an alternate route to Skelton Lake. Common destinations beyond Duck Pass include Duck Lake, with an intense, deep-blue color, and nearby Purple Lake.

Download map for trail names in this area.

https://www.fs.usda.gov/Internet/FSE_DOCUMENTS/stelprdb5337629.pdf

description_map.need_to_know:
Duck Pass Area: 

Duck Pass permit may continue on the John Muir Trail, either north or south. 

  • No campfires in Coldwater Canyon, Duck Creek or Purple Lake; and no campfires above 10,000 ft. Map of Campfire Restrictions can be found on the forest webpage. 
  • Bear containers are required for storage of food and trash. 
  • No camping within 300 ft. of the outlet of Duck Lake or Purple Lake. 
  • Emerald Lake trail and the trail to Ram Lake are not recommended for stock. 
  • John Muir Wilderness regulations apply.  

USFS Webpage for: Duck Pass. 

https://www.fs.usda.gov/recarea/inyo/recreation/hiking/recarea/?recid=20496

444.name: Duck Pass

445.description:
Starting east of Sherwin Campground near Mammoth Lakes, the Valentine Lake trail is one of two trails that go to Valentine Lake. The alternate Sherwin Creek trail climbs past Sherwin Lakes to join the Valentine Lake trail near the wilderness boundary at 8,900 feet elevation. The trail continues climbing past Lost Lake to end at Valentine Lake.

Download map for trail names in this area.

https://www.fs.usda.gov/Internet/FSE_DOCUMENTS/stelprdb5337630.pdf

description_map.need_to_know:
Valentine Lake Area: 

Valentine Lake trail does not connect to the John Muir Trail.

  • Special approval is required for commercial use. This trail is not recommended for stock.  
  • Camping at Sherwin Lakes is non-wilderness/ dispersed camping and requires a California campfire permit to operate a stove 
  • No campfires above 10,000 ft. 
  • Food and refuse must be stored in a container designed to prevent access by bears, or counter-balanced at least 15 feet above the ground and 10 feet horizontally from a tree trunk (where containers are not required) 
  • John Muir Wilderness regulations apply.  

USFS Webpage for: Valentine Lake. 

https://www.fs.usda.gov/recarea/inyo/recreation/hiking/recarea/?recid=20462

445.name: Valentine Lake

446.description: Accessed from a rough four wheel drive road that ascends the east bank of Laurel Creek, the Laurel Lakes trail enters the wilderness just before Laurel Lake. Climbing up the canyon, the trail continues southeast over a saddle and descends to Edith Lake and Lake Genevieve, where it meets the Convict Canyon Trail.

description_map.need_to_know:
Laurel Lakes Area:

Laurel Lakes trail does not connect to the John Muir Trail.

  • No campfires above 10,000ft.
  • Special fishing regulations, only artificial lures may be used. Minimum size limit: 14 inches total length. Limit 2 trout.
  • Food and refuse must be stored in a container designed to prevent access by bears, or counter-balanced at least 15 feet above the ground and 10 feet horizontally from a tree trunk (where containers are not required).
  • John Muir Wilderness regulations apply.

USFS Webpage for: Laurel Lakes

https://www.fs.usda.gov/recarea/inyo/recreation/recarea/?recid=20464&actid=50

446.name: Laurel Lakes

447.description:
After following the north shore of Convict Lake, this rugged trail climbs a steep, v-shaped canyon with several exposed sections. Within three miles from the trail's start, a challenging stream crossing blocks the way. Many groups turn back at this point, especially during the high water of spring thaw.

Above Mildred Lake a trail continues to climb steeply for another mile to a colorful and impressively large Dorothy lake. Fishing and campsites are abundant in this vicinity. Hikers can continue on a trail near Dorothy's outlet that leads to Lake Genevieve.

To avoid the difficult water crossings use the Laurel Canyon trail instead.

Download map for trail names in this area.

description_map.need_to_know:
Convict Creek Area:

This trail has a water crossing that many find to be a serious obstacle.  

Convict Creek permit does not allow camping at Convict Lake; does not connect to John Muir Trail.

  • Special approval is required for commercial use. Trail is not recommended for stock. 
  • No campfires at Mildred Lake; and no campfires above 10,000 ft., look at USFS Webpage for campfire restriction maps. 
  • Food and refuse must be stored in a container designed to prevent access by bears, or counter-balanced at least 15 feet above the ground and 10 feet horizontally from a tree trunk (where containers are not required).
  • John Muir Wilderness regulations apply.  

USFS Webpage for: Convict Canyon.

447.name: Convict Creek

448.description:
Abundant wildflowers mixed with sage fill the lower part of McGee Canyon on the way to Horsetail Falls. Water crossings may be high during spring snow melt. As the canyon turns west and climbs into aspen and lodgepole pine, side trails lead to Steelhead Lake and Baldwin Canyon. Farther up the canyon are Big McGee and Little McGee Lakes. Crossing over 11,875 ft. McGee Pass leads to Horse Heaven and Tully Hole on the John Muir Trail.

Download map for trail names in this area.

https://www.fs.usda.gov/Internet/FSE_DOCUMENTS/stelprdb5337630.pdf

description_map.need_to_know:
McGee Pass Area:

  • No campfires. Map of campfire restrictions are on USFS Webpage.

  • Food and refuse must be stored in a container designed to prevent access by bears, or counter-balanced at least 15 feet above the ground and 10 feet horizontally from a tree trunk (where containers are not required).

  • Check the area map for the correct trail name. There are other McGee Creeks in Inyo National forest that are a different reservation.

  • John Muir Wilderness regulations apply.

USFS Webpage for: McGee Creek.

https://www.fs.usda.gov/recarea/inyo/recreation/hiking/recarea/?recid=20400

448.name: McGee Pass

449.description:
Starting near the pack station by Rock Creek Lake, the Hilton Lakes trail leads you through a forest of whitebark and lodgepole pines before it enters a basin with many lakes, including Hilton and Davis Lakes.

Download map for trail names in this area.

https://www.fs.usda.gov/Internet/FSE_DOCUMENTS/stelprdb5337631.pdf

description_map.need_to_know:
Hilton Lakes Area:

Permit for Hilton Lakes includes trail from Rock Creek Road and Hilton Creek trail from Lake Crowley; does not include Mosquito Flat Trailhead.

  • No campfires. 
  • Food and refuse must be stored in a container designed to prevent access by bears, or counter-balanced at least 15 feet above the ground and 10 feet horizontally from a tree trunk (where containers are not required). 
  • Check the area map to select the correct trail name. This permit does not include trips going toward Mono Pass, Tamarack Lakes or Little Lakes Valley. 
  • John Muir Wilderness regulations apply.  

USFS Webpage for: Hilton Lakes. 

https://www.fs.usda.gov/recarea/inyo/recreation/hiking/recarea/?recid=20402

449.name: Hilton Lakes

450.description:
Tamarack Lake trail climbs the slope above the eastern shore of Rock Creek Lake. This trail offers non-wilderness travel options along the shoulder of Wheeler Ridge and Sand Canyon Road. To enter the John Muir wilderness, follow the east fork of Rock Creek into a broad valley and on to Kenneth and Dorothy Lakes. The side trail to Francis Lake is not recommended for stock. At the upper end of the valley the trail climbs to Tamarack Lake and Buck Lake near the top of Wheeler Ridge.

Check the area map to select the correct trail name. This permit does not include Little Lakes Valley, Mono Pass, or Hilton Lakes.

Download map for trail names in this area.

https://www.fs.usda.gov/Internet/FSE_DOCUMENTS/stelprdb5337631.pdf

description_map.need_to_know:
Tamarack Lakes Area: 

Permit for Tamarack Lakes does not include Little Lakes Valley; does not connect to the John Muir Trail. 

  • No campfires in this area 
  • Food and refuse must be stored in a container designed to prevent access by bears, or counter-balanced at least 15 feet above the ground and 10 feet horizontally from a tree trunk (where containers are not required) 
  • John Muir Wilderness regulations apply  

USFS Webpage for: Tamarack Lakes. 

https://www.fs.usda.gov/recarea/inyo/recreation/hiking/recarea/?recid=20408

450.name: Tamarack Lakes

451.description:
This easy hike to a beautiful chain of lakes makes the Little Lakes Valley trail popular for fishing, day hikes and beginning backpackers. Glaciers carved this extensive chain of lakes, both large and small. Wildflowers bloom in the high elevation framed by the spectacular 13,000 foot peaks of Bear Creek Spire, Mt Dade, Mt. Abbot and Mt. Mills. Some evidence of historical mining equipment can be seen, along with an old road bed at Morgan Pass. 

Little Lakes Valley trail does not include Ruby Lake or Mono Pass. 

The trail between Morgan Lakes and Pine Creek is not advised, rock slide caused significant irreparable damage.

Download map for trail names in this area. 

https://www.fs.usda.gov/Internet/FSE_DOCUMENTS/stelprdb5337631.pdf

description_map.need_to_know:
Little Lakes Valley Area:

Backpackers starting on this trail are allowed to camp at the trailhead the night before their trip (10 walk in sites).

  • No campfires anywhere in this valley.

  • Bear containers are required for storage of food and trash.

  • John Muir Wilderness regulations apply.

USFS Webpage for: Little Lakes Valley.

https://www.fs.usda.gov/recarea/inyo/recreation/hiking/recarea/?recid=20404

451.name: Little Lakes Valley

452.description:
The Italy Pass trail separates from the Pine Creek Pass trail near Honeymoon Lake. Before reaching Italy Pass, the trail goes through Granite Park and the Chalfant Lake area. A faint trail, occasionally marked with stone cairns crosses Italy Pass and descends past Jumble Lake and Lake Italy, named for its shape like the map of Italy.

Routes continue into the Bear Lakes Basin and Hilgard Branch eventually reaching the John Muir Trail near Bear Creek. This area is not recommended for stock.

Download map for trail names in this area.

https://www.fs.usda.gov/Internet/FSE_DOCUMENTS/stelprdb5337632.pdf

description_map.need_to_know:
Italy Pass Area:

Permit for Italy Pass does not include trips starting over Pine Creek Pass or Gable Lakes. 

  • Special approval is required for commercial use of this area.  
  • No campfires above the wilderness boundary in Pine Creek Canyon; and no campfires above 10,000 ft. look at USFS Webpage for campfire restriction maps. 
  • Food and refuse must be stored in a container designed to prevent access by bears, or counter-balanced at least 15 feet above the ground and 10 feet horizontally from a tree trunk (where containers are not required).  
  • John Muir Wilderness regulations apply.  

USFS Webpage for: Italy Pass. 

https://www.fs.usda.gov/recarea/inyo/recreation/hiking/recarea/?recid=37195

452.name: Italy Pass

454.description:
Rich in mining history, the Gable Lakes trail starts deep in the canyon behind Mount Tom and climbs past historic sites that once transported miners up to the mine in ore buckets. Visitors should remember that the Antiquities Act prohibits the damage or removal of artifacts. Hike four miles up this rocky, steep and exposed trail to reach fishless Gable Lakes.

Download map for trail names in this area.

https://www.fs.usda.gov/Internet/FSE_DOCUMENTS/stelprdb5337632.pdf

description_map.need_to_know:
Gable Lakes Area: 

Permit for Gable Lakes does not include entry via Pine Creek Pass or Italy Pass. Gable Lakes trail does not connect to the John Muir Trail.

  • Special approval is required for commercial use. Trail is not recommended for stock.  
  • No campfires above 10,000 ft. 
  • Food and refuse must be stored in a container designed to prevent access by bears, or counter-balanced at least 15 feet above the ground and 10 feet horizontally from a tree trunk (where containers are not required). 
  • John Muir Wilderness regulations apply.  

USFS Webpage for: Gable Lake. 

https://www.fs.usda.gov/recarea/inyo/recreation/hiking/recarea/?recid=20364

454.name: Gable Lakes

455.description:
The trail to Horton Lakes can be found by following a rough dirt road beyond Bishop's Buttermilk Country. The Horton Lakes Trail climbs 3.8 miles to Lower Horton Lake at the foot of Mt. Tom.

Download map for trail names in this area.

https://www.fs.usda.gov/Internet/FSE_DOCUMENTS/stelprdb5337632.pdf

description_map.need_to_know:
Horton Lakes Area:  

Horton Lakes trail does not connect to the John Muir Trail. 

  • No campfires at Lower Horton Lake; and no campfires above 10,000 ft. Map of campfire restrictions is on the USFS Webpage. 
  • Food and refuse must be stored in a container designed to prevent access by bears, or counter-balanced at least 15 feet above the ground and 10 feet horizontally from a tree trunk (where containers are not required). 
  • John Muir Wilderness regulations apply.  

Driving directions can be found on the forest webpage. 

USFS Webpage for: Horton Lakes. 

https://www.fs.usda.gov/recarea/inyo/recreation/hiking/recarea/?recid=21066

455.name: Horton Lakes

456.description:
Beginning near North Lake and the colorful Piute Crags, Piute Pass trail starts in pine and quaking aspen. The trail climbs steadily up this glacier carved canyon along the North Fork of Bishop Creek passing numerous small ponds, Loch Leven and Piute Lake.

From Piute Pass (11,420 ft) explore Humphreys Basin beyond the pass, with high alpine lakes and tarns bordered by Glacier Divide and Mt. Humphreys, or descend the trail to Hutchinson Meadow and the John Muir Trail junction at Piute Creek.

Piute Pass and Bishop Pass trail are the end points for the popular North Lake to South Lake Loop.

Piute Pass trail does not include Lamarck Lakes.

Download map for trail names in this area.

https://www.fs.usda.gov/Internet/FSE_DOCUMENTS/stelprdb5337633.pdf

description_map.need_to_know:
Piute Pass Area:

Piute Pass permit may continue on John Muir Trail.

  • No campfires from the trailhead to Piute Pass, or above 10,000 ft. north of Glacier Divide 
  • Food and refuse must be stored in a container designed to prevent access by bears, or counter-balanced at least 15 feet above the ground and 10 feet from a tree trunk (where containers are not required) 
  • No parking in campground, park at North Lake 
  • John Muir Wilderness regulations apply 
  • Sequoia and Kings Canyon regulations apply if entering the park (includes no pets, no bear spray, group size limit 8 in Darwin Canyon or Dusy Basin, two night camping limit in Dusy Basin).  

USFS Webpage for: Piute Pass 

https://www.fs.usda.gov/recarea/inyo/recreation/hiking/recarea/?recid=21048

456.name: Piute Pass

457.description:
Beginning at Bishop Creek, the Tyee trail crosses over a sturdy bridge near Willow Campground at 9,000 ft. elevation. This steep trail with many switch backs has great views of the Inconsolable Range and the peaks that surround South Lake. The Tyee Lakes are near the top of Table Mountain. A less distinct trail continues on to connect with the George Lake Trail over Table Mountain.

Download map for trail names in this area

https://www.fs.usda.gov/Internet/FSE_DOCUMENTS/stelprdb5337638.pdf

description_map.need_to_know:
Tyee Lakes Area: 

Permit for Tyee Lakes does not include Sabrina Basin, Bishop Pass, Treasure Lakes, or the John Muir Trail.

  • Special approval is required for commercial use. This trail is not recommended for stock.  
  • No campfires 
  • Food and refuse must be stored in a container designed to prevent access by bears, or counter-balanced at least 15 feet above the ground and 10 feet horizontally from a tree trunk (where containers are not required) 
  • John Muir Wilderness regulations apply.  

USFS Webpage for: Tyee Lakes. 

https://www.fs.usda.gov/recarea/inyo/recreation/hiking/recarea/?recid=21082

457.name: Tyee Lakes

458.description:
Starting at South Lake, the trail is combined with the Bishop Pass trail until the first trail junction. Follow the Treasure Lakes trail to a beautiful, less visited, granite basin separated from the Bishop Creek Canyon by Hurd Peak. These high alpine lakes are rimmed by the Sierra Crest, dominated by Mount Thompson and Mount Goode.

Treasure Lakes trail does not include Bishop Pass.

Download map for trail names in this area.

https://www.fs.usda.gov/Internet/FSE_DOCUMENTS/stelprdb5337638.pdf

description_map.need_to_know:
Treasure Lakes Area: 

Permit for Treasure Lakes does not include Bishop Pass entry; does not connect to John Muir Trail. 

  • No campfires 
  • Bear containers are required for storage of food and trash 
  • Check the area map to select the correct trail name, for the Treasure Lakes near Mount Dade use the Little Lakes Valley trail 
  • John Muir Wilderness regulations apply.  

USFS Webpage for: Treasure Lakes. 

https://www.fs.usda.gov/recarea/inyo/recreation/hiking/recarea/?recid=20360

458.name: Treasure Lakes

459.description:
Starting at beautiful South Lake, the Bishop Pass trail climbs the valley between the Inconsolable Range and Hurd Peak. The trail climbs several granite benches, each holding lakes and ponds. A side trail, the Chocolate Lake loop, is a popular alternate route around Chocolate Peak, rejoining the main trail at Long Lake. The highest lakes above Saddlerock Lake are tinted with glacial melt at the foot of Mt. Thompson and Mt. Goode. Over Bishop Pass is the backcountry of Kings Canyon National Park, with the trail continuing through Dusy Basin to LeConte Canyon where it meets the John Muir Trail.

Refer to the Inyo National Forest Motor Vehicle Map to identify the dirt roads in this area.

Download map for trail names in this area.

description_map.need_to_know:
Bishop Pass Area:

Permit for Bishop Pass may continue on John Muir Trail.

  • No campfires above 10,000 ft. 
  • Bear containers are required for storage of food and trash. 
  • Check the area map to select the correct trail. Trips going toward Treasure Lakes are a different reservation. 
  • The Chocolate Lake Loop is not recommended for stock. 
  • John Muir Wilderness regulations apply. 
  • Sequoia and Kings Canyon wilderness regulations apply if entering the National Parks (includes no pets, no bear spray, two night camp limit for Dusy Basin, off trail group size of limit eight in Dusy and Palisade Basin)  

USFS Webpage for: Bishop Pass - South Lake

459.name: Bishop Pass -South Lake

460.description:
Starting from Big Pine Creek, Glacier Lodge road, the trail to Baker Lake climbs several miles of sage-covered slopes and eventually winds through stands of Jeffrey pines to climb past Grouse Spring and High Meadow. Views of the Middle Palisade and Disappointment Peak can be seen as you climb over the ridge. The trail follows Baker Creek, to Baker Lake, and then descends into Bishop Creek Canyon past Green Lake and Brown Lake. Alternate starting point from Bishop Creek Canyon are Parchers Resort or South Lake parking lot.

Baker Lake Trail does not include locations in Big Pine North or South Fork.

Download map for trail names in this area.

description_map.need_to_know:
Baker Lake Area:

This permit does not include Big Pine North Fork. Check the area map to select the correct trail.

Special approval required for commercial use.

  • Brown and Green Lake are not in the wilderness boundary.

  • No campfires.

  • Food and refuse must be stored in a container designed to prevent access by bears, or counter-balanced at least 15 feet above the ground and 10 feet horizontally from a tree trunk (where containers are not required).

  • John Muir Wilderness regulations apply.

USFS Webpage for: Baker and Green Lakes

460.name: Baker and Green Lakes

461.description:
Big Pine South Fork trail to Brainard and Finger Lakes climbs beneath the Norman Clyde and Middle Palisade Glaciers with views of the jagged crest of the Middle Palisades.

The bridge across the South Fork Creek was destroyed by avalanche (spring 2011) so expect to get your feet wet and use caution with high spring runoff. The trail beyond Willow Lake becomes indistinct with rock cairns marking the way to the upper lakes.

Download map for trail names in this area.

description_map.need_to_know:
Big Pine South Fork Area:

 

This permit does not include the North Fork. Check the area map to select the correct trail.

  

  • No campfires. 
  • Food and refuse must be stored in a container designed to prevent access by bears, or counter-balanced at least 15 feet above the ground and 10 feet horizontally from a tree trunk (where containers are not required). 
  • Stock is not recommended beyond Willow Lake. 
  • John Muir Wilderness regulations apply. 
  • Sequoia and Kings Canyon wilderness regulations apply if entering the park. No pets, no bear spray, group size limit of eight in Palisade Basin.  

USFS Webpage for: Big Pine Creek South Fork.

461.name: Big Pine Creek South Fork

462.description:
Located between Kid Mountain and Birch Mountain, this steep trail ends at Birch Lake. The trail starts from an old jeep road that heads west from McMurry Meadows. Starting on the north side of Birch Creek the trail climbs into the broad valley north of Birch Mountain until it crosses the stream just below Birch Lake. 

Refer to the Inyo National Forest Motor Vehicle Map to identify the dirt roads in this area. 

Download map for trail names in this area.

description_map.need_to_know:
Birch Lake Area:

Birch Lake trail does not connect to the John Muir Trail.

  • Special approval required for commercial use. The trail is not recommended for stock 1/3 mile below Birch Lake.
  • The dirt road to the trailhead near McMurry Meadows is rough and rocky. High clearance 4x4 is recomended. Refer to the Inyo National Forest Motor Vehicle Map to identify the correct road. 
  • No campfires above 10,400 ft. 
  • Food and refuse must be stored in a container designed to prevent access by bears, or counter-balanced at least 15 feet above the ground and 10 feet horizontally from a tree trunk (where containers are not required). 
  • John Muir Wilderness regulations apply.  

USFS Webpage for: Birch Lake.

462.name: Birch Lake

463.description:
Red Lake is at the base of Split Mountain. The trail to Red Lake is 4.3 miles long if you are able to drive to the end of a rugged dirt road. You may need to walk a few more miles if you do not have a high clearance four wheel drive vehicle. Shovel, pry bar and tall jack recommended. Refer to the Inyo National Forest Motor Vehicle Map and follow directions carefully that identify what roads to follow to the trailhead. Roads that seem more direct are not open to public access. Please respect private property signs and locked gates. 

Download map for trail names in this area. 

https://www.fs.usda.gov/Internet/FSE_DOCUMENTS/stelprdb5337640.pdf

description_map.need_to_know:
Red Lake Area: 

Get road directions. High clearance four wheel drive needed for this rough road.

  • Special approval required for commercial use. Not recommended for stock.   
  • Beware of rock fall and unstable terrain especially during rain event or snow melt. 
  • No campfires above 10,400 ft. 
  • Food and refuse must be stored in a container designed to prevent access by bears, or counter-balanced at least 15 feet above the ground and 10 feet horizontally from a tree trunk (where containers are not required) 
  • John Muir Wilderness regulations apply  

Sequoia and Kings Canyon regulations apply if entering the National Park (includes no pets, no bear spray).  

USFS Webpage for: Red Lake. 

https://www.fs.usda.gov/recarea/inyo/recreation/hiking/recarea/?recid=20326

463.name: Red Lake

464.description:
Baxter Pass trail is steep and rugged. Starting near Oak Creek, the trail climbs more than 6,000 feet to the Sierra Crest at Baxter Pass. It pays to start early in the day for this high elevation pass.

It’s approximately eight miles to the top of the pass where the trail goes into Kings Canyon National Park, a total of 13 miles to the John Muir Trail junction. No camping at Bullfrog Lake, there is a two night camping limit at Charlotte or Kearsarge Lakes and in the Rae Lakes area there is a one night camping limit per lake from Glen Pass to Dollar Lake.

A smaller group size limit applies to hikers visiting 60 Lakes or Gardiner Basin.

Download map for trail names in this area.

description_map.need_to_know:
Baxter Pass Area:

  • Special approval required for commercial use. This trail is not recommended for stock.
  • No campfires above 10,400 ft. 
  • Food and refuse must be stored in a container designed to prevent access by bears, or counter-balanced at least 15 feet above the ground and 10 feet horizontally from a tree trunk (where containers are not required). 
  • John Muir Wilderness regulations apply. 
  • Sequoia and Kings Canyon wilderness regulations apply if entering the National Park (includes no pets; no bear spray; off trail group size limit 8)  

USFS Webpage for: Baxter Pass

464.name: Baxter Pass

465.description:
The Kearsarge Pass trail begins at an elevation of 9,100 ft. at Onion Valley and climbs through forests and alpine tundra past several lakes including Big and Little Pothole, Gilbert, and Flower Lakes on the way to Kearsarge Pass at 11,700 ft. Beyond the pass the trail continues into Kings Canyon National Park and joins the John Muir Trail near Bullfrog Lake. It is 6.5 miles from the trailhead to the John Muir Trail junction, making this a popular choice for going to the Rae Lakes area and this section of the John Muir Trail.

Download map for trail names in this area.

https://www.fs.usda.gov/Internet/FSE_DOCUMENTS/stelprdb5337642.pdf

description_map.need_to_know:
Kearsarge Pass Area: 

High bear activity in this area.

  • No campfires. 
  • No camping at Bullfrog Lake. Rae Lakes area, one night limit per lake between Glen Pass and Dollar Lake. Two night limit at Charlotte and Kearsarge Lakes. 
  • Bear containers are required for storage of food and trash. 
  • John Muir Wilderness regulations apply. 
  • Sequoia and Kings Canyon wilderness regulations apply if entering the National Park (includes no pets; no bear spray; group size limit eight for Sphinx Creek and Brewer Range, Sixty Lakes and Gardner Basin areas)  

USFS Webpage for: Kearsarge Pass. 

https://www.fs.usda.gov/recarea/inyo/recreation/hiking/recarea/?recid=20784

465.name: Kearsarge Pass

466.description:
Starting along Symmes Creek, the Shepherd Pass trail climbs a demanding 6,000 feet from the valley floor to the 12,000-foot Shepherd Pass where it crosses the Sierra Crest. Descending into Sequoia and Kings Canyon National Parks the trail continues to the Tyndall Creek junction of the John Muir Trail. It pays to be fit and start early for this pass. In many years, a large steep snow bank lingers year-round at the top of this challenging pass and may be impassable to stock.

Download map for trail names in this area.

https://www.fs.usda.gov/Internet/FSE_DOCUMENTS/stelprdb5337642.pdf

description_map.need_to_know:
Shepherd Pass Area: 

  • No campfires at Anvil Camp; no campfires above 10,400 ft. 
  • Food and refuse must be stored in a container designed to prevent access by bears, or counter-balanced at least 15 feet above the ground and 10 feet horizontally from a tree trunk (where containers are not required) 
  • John Muir Wilderness regulations apply 
  • Sequoia and Kings Canyon wilderness regulations apply if entering the park (includes no pets; no bear spray; group size limit eight for Sphinx Creek and Brewer Range area).  

USFS Webpage for: Shepherd Pass. 

https://www.fs.usda.gov/recarea/inyo/recreation/hiking/recarea/?recid=20796

466.name: Shepherd Pass

467.description:
Follow George Creek up this steep canyon, named for Chief George, a Piute leader in the 1860s. This unmaintained cross-country route climbs more than 6,000 vertical feet to the area near Mt. Williamson, Trojan Peak, and Mt. Barnard. Trips up Bairs Creek are included in this permit. Check guidebooks for route descriptions.

A high clearance 4x4 vehicle is recommended to reach the trailhead.

Please be respectful of wildlife as you pass through habitat for the endangered Sierra Nevada bighorn sheep.

Check avalanche conditions before attempting winter ascents.

Download map for trail names in this area.

https://www.fs.usda.gov/Internet/FSE_DOCUMENTS/stelprdb5337642.pdf

description_map.need_to_know:
George Creek Area: 

Permit includes off trail routes via George Creek or Bairs Creek to Mt Williamson; does not connect to the John Muir Trail.

  • Special approval is required for commercial guide use of this area. Not recommended for stock.  
  • No campfires above 10,400 ft. elevation. 
  • Food and refuse must be stored in a container designed to prevent access by bears, or counter-balanced at least 15 feet above the ground and 10 feet horizontally from a tree trunk (where containers are not required). 
  • John Muir Wilderness regulations apply. 
  • Sequoia and Kings Canyon wilderness regulations apply if entering the National Park.  

USFS Webpage for: George Creek - Mt. Williamson 

https://www.fs.usda.gov/recarea/inyo/recreation/hiking/recarea/?recid=70844

467.name: George Creek

468.description:
Meysan Lake trail is used to approach Lone Pine Peak. The trail begins near Whitney Portal Campground and goes past Little Meysan and Grass Lake. Meysan Lake at the foot of Mt Irvine and Mt Mallory is at the end of the trail.

Day hiking on Meysan Lakes trail does not require a permit. This trail does not go to Mt Whitney. Trips into the Mt Whitney Zone have different permit requirements.

Download map for trail names in this area.

https://www.fs.usda.gov/Internet/FSE_DOCUMENTS/stelprdb5337643.pdf

description_map.need_to_know:
Meysan Lake Area:

Permit for Meysan Lake trail does not include entry on Mt Whitney trail. 

  • No Campfires 
  • Food and refuse must be stored in a container designed to prevent access by bears, or counter-balanced at least 15 feet above the ground and 10 feet horizontally from a tree trunk (where containers are not required). 
  • John Muir Wilderness regulations apply. 
  • Sequoia and Kings Canyon wilderness regulations apply if entering the National Park. (includes no pets, no bear spray, group size limit of eight in Miter Basin and Crabtree Lakes)  

USFS Webpage for: Meysan Lakes. 

https://www.fs.usda.gov/recarea/inyo/recreation/hiking/recarea/?recid=20804

468.name: Meysan Lake

471.description:
Traveling north from Kennedy Meadows this trail is part of the Pacific Crest Trail (PCT) as it enters South Sierra Wilderness. For the first few miles the trail follows the South Fork of the Kern River. Water may be scarce after the trail leaves the river and goes into arid pinyon and juniper woodlands to eventually gain elevation and continue north into forests of Jeffrey and foxtail pine.

The less visited Wildrose trail offers the option of making a loop trip back to Kennedy Meadows.

Hikers going 500 miles or more on the PCT should contact the Pacific Crest Trail Association for a through hiking pass.

Download map for trail names in this area.

https://www.fs.usda.gov/Internet/FSE_DOCUMENTS/stelprdb5337645.pdf

description_map.need_to_know:
Kennedy Meadows Area: 

This non-quota trail gives unlimited entry to South Sierra Wilderness and points beyond. Book your trip about a week before your entry date to allow time to check in by email.

  • Food and refuse must be stored in a container designed to prevent access by bears, or counter-balanced at least 15 feet above the ground and 10 feet horizontally from a tree trunk (where containers are not required). 
  • South Sierra Wilderness regulations apply. 
  • Golden Trout Wilderness regulations apply north of Olancha Peak. 
  • Sequoia and Kings Canyon wilderness regulations apply if entering the park (includes no pets, no bear spray).  

USFS Webpage for: Kennedy Meadows

https://www.fs.usda.gov/recarea/inyo/recreation/hiking/recarea/?recid=81827

471.name: Kennedy Meadows (Non Quota)

473.description:
Beginning on the southern border of the Golden Trout Wilderness, the Black Rock trail goes to Casa Vieja Meadow and Jordan Hot Spring as it passes through rugged, forested terrain to end at the Wild and Scenic section of the Kern River near Soda Flat. Connecting trails circle around Kern Peak with many options for loop trips of various lengths.

Download map for trail names in this area.

description_map.need_to_know:
Blackrock Trail Area:

Contact Sequoia National Forest regarding effects of 2020 wildfire in this area.

Blackrock is a non-quota trail with unlimited entry to Golden Trout Wilderness. Book your trip about a week before your entry date to allow time to check in by email.

  • Food and refuse must be stored in a container designed to prevent access by bears, or counter-balanced at least 15 feet above the ground and 10 feet horizontally from a tree trunk (where containers are not required). 
  • Golden Trout Wilderness regulations apply.  

For area information, contact Kern River Ranger District, Sequoia National Forest, (760) 376-3781 

USFS Webpage for: Blackrock.

473.name: Blackrock (Non Quota)

474.description:
Fish Creek trail follows the general route of an old wagon trail. Starting near Reds Meadow Resort (shuttle stop # 10) or the Rainbow Falls trailhead (shuttle stop #8) the trail passes multiple junctions with the John Muir, Devils Postpile and Rainbow Falls trails. Fish Creek trail follows Crater Creek to the Fish Creek Valley. Eleven miles down the trail is the popular Iva Belle hot springs. Beyond Iva Belle, the trail goes to Cascade Valley and eventually connects to the John Muir and Pacific Crest Trails near Purple Lake or Tully Hole.

A permit for Fish Creek trail does not include starting on the John Muir Trail at Reds Meadow or Devils Postpile.

Download map for trail names in this area.

https://www.fs.usda.gov/Internet/FSE_DOCUMENTS/stelprdb5337628.pdf

description_map.need_to_know:
Fish Creek Area: 

Permit includes trips into Fish Valley and Cascade Valley; not for starting on JMT at Devils Postplie/ Reds Meadow.

  • No campfires above 10,000 ft. 
  • Active bear area, secure your food and trash. 
  • Food and refuse must be stored in a container designed to prevent access by bears, or where cans are not required counter-balance at least 15 feet above the ground and 10 feet horizontally from a tree trunk. 
  • Ansel Adams Wilderness regulations apply.  

All visitors to Reds Meadow Valley pay a transportation fee which allows use of the mandatory shuttle bus. Call Mammoth Lakes Welcome Center for more shuttle information (760) 924-5500. 

USFS Webpage for: Fish Creek. 

https://www.fs.usda.gov/recarea/inyo/recreation/hiking/recarea/?recid=20502

474.name: Fish Creek

475.description:
Trail Pass goes to the south of Horseshoe Meadows and connects to trails in the northeastern portion of Golden Trout Wilderness. Small streams meander through tree rimmed meadows in this wilderness area, which is named for California's state fish. 

This trail is popular with horseback riders for its gentle grade and convenient location to Horseshoe Meadows Equestrian Campground. 

Trips going north on the Pacific Crest Trail need a Cottonwood Pass permit.

Download map for trail names in this area. 

https://www.fs.usda.gov/Internet/FSE_DOCUMENTS/stelprdb5337644.pdf

description_map.need_to_know:
Trail Pass Area: 

This non-quota trail gives unlimited entry to the Golden Trout Wilderness. Call the wilderness permit office about a week before the trip for assistance booking this permit. 

  • Food and refuse must be stored in a container designed to prevent access by bears, or counter-balanced at least 15 feet above the ground and 10 feet horizontally from a tree trunk (where containers are not required) 
  • Check the area map to select the correct trail name. Trips going north on the Pacific Crest Trail need a Cottonwood Pass permit 
  • Golden Trout Wilderness regulations apply. No campfires at Rocky Basin Lakes or Chicken Spring Lake.  

USFS Webpage for: Trail Pass 

https://www.fs.usda.gov/recarea/inyo/recreation/hiking/recarea/?recid=20814&actid=51

475.name: Trail Pass (Non Quota)

476.description:
Traveling more than 200 miles, the John Muir Trail extends from Happy Isles in Yosemite National Park to the top of Mount Whitney.

This section of the trail is south of Devils Postpile National Monument near Reds Meadow. This permit does not include Yosemite.

From the Devils Postpile Visitor Center (shuttle stop #6) it is less than a mile to a bridge across the river and the junction with the John Muir Trail. Following the trail southward you will pass the stone columns of Devils Postpile. If you will exit at Whitney Portal select the exit point of Mt. Whitney-Trail Crest Exit on your permit.

Download map for trail names in this area.

https://www.fs.usda.gov/Internet/FSE_DOCUMENTS/stelprdb5337628.pdf

description_map.need_to_know:
John Muir Trail South of Devils Postpile Area: 

Permit does not go to Yosemite.

  • No campfires above 10,000 ft. or at Duck Creek or Purple Lake. Map of campfire restrictions on USFS Webpage. 
  • Bear containers are required for storage of food and trash. 
  • Ansel Adams and John Muir Wilderness regulations apply. 
  • Sequoia and Kings Canyon wilderness regulations apply if entering the National Park (includes no pets, no bear spray)  

All visitors to Reds Meadow Valley pay a transportation fee which allows use of the mandatory shuttle bus. Call Mammoth Lakes Welcome Center for shuttle information (760) 924-5500

USFS Webpage for: John Muir Trail South of Devils Postpile. 

https://www.fs.usda.gov/recarea/inyo/recreation/hiking/recarea/?recid=21214

476.name: John Muir Trail South of Devils Postpile

477.description:
Experience many biologic zones as this trail begins in the sage environment of the Owens Valley with a strenuous climb of more than 6,000 feet in 6.5 miles up Taboose Creek Canyon. Crossing over 11,350 ft. Taboose Pass between Cardinal Mountain and Goodale Mountain the trail enters Kings Canyon National Park and joins the John Muir Trail at the headwaters of the South Fork of the Kings River, south of Mather Pass.

Download map for trail names in this area.

https://www.fs.usda.gov/Internet/FSE_DOCUMENTS/stelprdb5337641.pdf

description_map.need_to_know:
Taboose Pass Area: 

  • Many hazards remain in this area from 2019 wildfire including potential rock fall. Beware of unstable terrain especially during rain event or snow melt.
  • This trail is not recommended for stock.  
  • No campfires above 10,400 ft. or along Taboose Creek 
  • Food and refuse must be stored in a container designed to prevent access by bears, or counter-balanced at least 15 feet above the ground and 10 feet horizontally from a tree trunk (where containers are not required) 
  • John Muir Wilderness regulations apply 
  • Sequoia and Kings Canyon wilderness regulations apply if entering the park (includes no pets, no bear spray).  

USFS Webpage for: Taboose Pass. 

https://www.fs.usda.gov/recarea/inyo/recreation/hiking/recarea/?recid=21116

477.name: Taboose Pass

478.description:
The Sawmill Pass trail is steep and strenuous. Starting near Division Creek, this trail climbs more than 6,700 feet to reach the Sierra Crest. The Sawmill Pass trail goes to the Woods Creek area of Kings Canyon National Park. There is no water or shade at the trailhead or along the first few miles of the trail. This route may be extremely hot during summer and early autumn.

Download map for trail names in this area.

https://www.fs.usda.gov/Internet/FSE_DOCUMENTS/stelprdb5337641.pdf

description_map.need_to_know:
Sawmill Pass Area:  

  • Campfires prohibited above 10,400 feet 
  • Food and refuse must be stored in a container designed to prevent access by bears, or counter-balanced at least 15 feet above the ground and 10 feet horizontally from a tree trunk (where containers are not required) 
  • John Muir Wilderness regulations apply 
  • Sequoia and Kings Canyon wilderness regulations apply if entering the National Park (includes no pets, no bear spray, group size limit eight for Sixty Lakes and Gardiner Basin areas).  

USFS Webpage for: Sawmill Pass. 

https://www.fs.usda.gov/recarea/inyo/recreation/hiking/recarea/?recid=20802

478.name: Sawmill Pass

480.description:
Haiwee Pass trail goes into the South Sierra Wilderness. The trail begins near 5,000 ft. elevation at the foot of the eastern Sierra and crosses over Haiwee Pass at 8,100 ft. elevation to reach the South Fork of Kern River. The trail is primitive and can be overgrown or faint in places. Bring a map and compass.

Download map for trail names in this area.

https://www.fs.usda.gov/Internet/FSE_DOCUMENTS/stelprdb5337645.pdf

description_map.need_to_know:
Haiwee Pass Area: 

This non-quota trail gives unlimited entry to South Sierra Wilderness. If your trip will continue north of Olancha Peak into Golden Trout Wilderness contact Inyo National Forest for how to book a permit.  

  • Not passable for stock. 
  • Food and refuse must be stored in a container designed to prevent access by bears, or counter-balanced at least 15 feet above the ground and 10 feet horizontally from a tree trunk (where containers are not required). 
  • If your travel plan stays within the South Sierra Wilderness no permit is required (carry a California Campfire Permit for stove use)
  • South Sierra Wilderness regulations apply.  

USFS Webpage for: Haiwee Pass. 

https://www.fs.usda.gov/recarea/inyo/recreation/hiking/recarea/?recid=20938

480.name: Haiwee Pass (Non Quota)

481.description:
Several trails start from the deep canyon cut by Pine Creek between Mount Tom and the Wheeler Crest. Pine Creek Pass trail goes to the Pine Lakes, along Pine Creek, and destinations beyond Pine Creek Pass. 

This is a popular choice to go to French Canyon, Royce Lakes, and Humphreys Basin. From the trailhead at Pine Creek to the John Muir Trail junction at Piute Creek is 20 miles. 

Pine Creek Pass trail does not include Italy Pass or Morgan Lakes.

Download map for trail names in this area. 

https://www.fs.usda.gov/Internet/FSE_DOCUMENTS/stelprdb5337632.pdf

description_map.need_to_know:
Pine Creek Pass Area:

  • No campfires above the wilderness boundary in Pine Creek Canyon; and no campfires above 10,000 ft. Map of campfire restrictions is on USFS Webpage

  • Food and refuse must be stored in a container designed to prevent access by bears, or counter-balanced at least 15 feet above the ground and 10 feet horizontally from a tree trunk (where containers are not required)

  • Trips going toward Gable Lakes or Italy Pass are a different reservation

  • John Muir Wilderness regulations apply

USFS Webpage for: Pine Creek.

https://www.fs.usda.gov/recarea/inyo/recreation/hiking/recarea/?recid=20370

481.name: Pine Creek

482.description:
Climbing above Sabrina Lake, the trail leads to a series of high alpine lakes surrounded by 13,000 ft. granite peaks on the Sierra Crest and bordered by the granite face of Thompson Ridge.

Many day hikers enjoy visiting Blue Lake (2.5 miles) with several trails continuing beyond Blue Lake. This basin is known for lake names with a story, like Hungry Packer, and Topsy Turvy. The side trail to Donkey and Baboon Lake is more rugged and is not recommended for stock. Farther up canyon Midnight and Moonlight Lakes are as beautiful as they sound. Bring a map if you want to find your way to Blue Heaven.

Download map for trail names in this area.

https://www.fs.usda.gov/Internet/FSE_DOCUMENTS/stelprdb5337633.pdf

description_map.need_to_know:
Sabrina Lake Area:

  • No campfires at Blue Lake; and no campfires above 10,400 ft.

  • Food and refuse must be stored in a container designed to prevent access by bears, or counter-balanced at least 15 feet above the ground and 10 feet horizontally from a tree trunk (where containers are not required). Beyond Blue Lake, bear containers are the only practical way to store food due to the lack of tall trees.

  • John Muir Wilderness regulations apply

USFS Webpage for: Sabrina.

https://www.fs.usda.gov/recarea/inyo/recreation/hiking/recarea/?recid=20374

482.name: Sabrina Lake

484.description:
Climbing the hillside on the south side of Sabrina Lake, the trail to George Lake climbs more than 2,500 feet up Table Mountain. Descending the other side of this broad mountaintop will bring you to Tyee Lakes.

George Lake trail does not include Sabrina Lakes Basin.

Download a map for trail names in this area.

https://www.fs.usda.gov/Internet/FSE_DOCUMENTS/stelprdb5337633.pdf

description_map.need_to_know:
George Lake Area:

Permit for George Lake may continue to Tyee Lakes. This permit does not include trips going toward Blue Lake, Sabrina Basin or connect to the John Muir Trail. 

  • No campfires above 10,400 ft. 
  • Food and refuse must be stored in a container designed to prevent access by bears, or counter-balanced at least 15 feet above the ground and 10 feet horizontally from a tree trunk (where containers are not required). 
  • Check the correct trail name, for Mt Williamson select George Creek or Shepherd Pass trail.
  • John Muir Wilderness regulations apply.  

USFS Webpage for: George Lake 

https://www.fs.usda.gov/recarea/inyo/recreation/hiking/recarea/?recid=37192

484.name: George Lake

485.description:
The High trail starts from Agnew Meadows (shuttle bus stop #1). Instead of crossing Agnew Meadow, the trail climbs partway up the east side of the canyon. The trail contours along the slope to the headwaters of the San Joaquin River with magnificent views across the valley of the Minarets, Mount Ritter and Banner Peak. Several trail junctions give options to Summit Lake, Agnew Pass, Clark Lakes, or Badger Lakes.

High trail is part of the Pacific Crest Trail and joins the John Muir Trail near Thousand Island Lake. This permit allows continuing on the John Muir Trail. This permit does not allow starting on Shadow Creek or River Trail.

Download map for trail names in this area.

https://www.fs.usda.gov/Internet/FSE_DOCUMENTS/stelprdb5337626.pdf

description_map.need_to_know:
High Trail -PCT Area:

  • No campfires at Thousand Island Lake, Garnet, Ruby, Emerald, Badger, or Clark Lakes; and no campfires above 10,000 ft. USFS Webpage has map of campfire restrictions.

  • Bear containers are required for storage of food and trash.

  • No camping within 300 feet of the outflow of Thousand Island Lake or Garnet Lake.

  • Ansel Adams Wilderness regulations apply.

  • Yosemite wilderness regulations apply if entering the National Park.

All visitors to Reds Meadow Valley pay a transportation fee which allows use of the mandatory shuttle bus. Call Mammoth Lakes Welcome Center for more shuttle information, (760) 924-5500.

USFS Webpage for: High Trail - PCT.

https://www.fs.usda.gov/recarea/inyo/recreation/hiking/recarea/?recid=20538

485.name: High Trail

486.description:
Traveling more than 200 miles, the John Muir Trail extends from the top of Mt. Whitney to Happy Isles in Yosemite National Park.

This section of the trail is north of Devils Postpile National Monument. From the Devils Postpile Visitor Center (shuttle stop #6) it is less than a mile to a bridge across the river and the junction with the John Muir Trail.

This permit is to follow the John Muir Trail northward as it climbs above Minaret Falls and goes past Johnston Lake, Trinity Lakes and destinations farther to the north, and can include all the way to Happy Isles in Yosemite.

This permit does not include Beck, Fern, Minaret Lakes or South of Devils Postpile.

Download map for trail names in this area.

https://www.fs.usda.gov/Internet/FSE_DOCUMENTS/stelprdb5337628.pdf

description_map.need_to_know:
John Muir Trail North of Devils Postpile:

  • Campfires are prohibited in much of this area. Map of campfire restrictions are on USFS Webpage. 
  • No camping at Shadow Lake, or near the outflow of Garnet Lake and Thousand Island Lake. 
  • Bear containers are required for storage of food and trash. 
  • Ansel Adams Wilderness regulations apply. 
  • Yosemite wilderness regulations apply if entering the park. No pets, no bear spray.  

All visitors to Reds Meadow Valley pay a transportation fee which allows use of mandatory shuttle bus. Call Mammoth Lakes Welcome Center for shuttle information (760) 924-5500

USFS Webpage: John Muir Trail North of Devils Postpile

https://www.fs.usda.gov/recarea/inyo/recreation/hiking/recarea/?recid=20542

486.name: John Muir Trail North of Devils Postpile

487.description:
This trail follows Shadow Creek to glacier fed lakes at the base of the Minarets and Mount Ritter.

Starting from Agnew Meadows (shuttle bus stop #1) the Shadow Creek and River trails are combined for the first three miles. At the trail junction near Olaine Lake, follow the Shadow Creek trail past Shadow Lake to join the John Muir Trail. Continue up the Shadow Creek trail to Ediza and Iceberg Lakes or you may go north or south on the John Muir Trail.

This permit does not include entry on the River Trail beyond the Shadow Creek junction. Permit may include exit on River or High Trail. Check the area map to select the correct trail name.

description_map.need_to_know:
Shadow Creek Area:

  • No campfires at Shadow, Ediza, or Iceberg Lakes; no campfires above 10,000 ft. Map of campfire restrictions are on USFS Webpage

  • No camping at Shadow Lake, Shadow Creek, and the east side of Ediza Lake

  • Bear containers are required for storage of food and trash

  • Ansel Adams Wilderness regulations apply

  • Not recommended for stock beyond Ediza Lake

  • Yosemite wilderness regulations apply if entering the park, no pets, no bear spray

All visitors to Reds Meadow Valley pay a transportation fee which allows use of the mandatory shuttle bus. Call Mammoth Lakes Welcome Center for more shuttle information, (760) 924-5500.

487.name: Shadow Creek

488.description:
Starting at the south end of Lundy Lake, the Lakes Canyon trail steadily climbs the narrow canyon between Gilcrest Peak and Mount Scowden. Interesting remains of mining history can be seen in this area.

Visitors should remember that the Antiquities Act protects all artifacts from being damaged or removed, so be sure to leave historical items where they are. It is 3.3 miles to reach Oneida Lake with Blue Lake nearby.

Download map for trail names in this area.

https://www.fs.usda.gov/Internet/FSE_DOCUMENTS/stelprdb5337621.pdf

description_map.need_to_know:
Lakes Canyon Area: 

Lakes Canyon is a non-quota trail with unlimited entry to Hoover Wilderness. Book your trip about a week before your entry date to allow time to check in by email.

  • No camping or entering the water of Crystal Lake. 
  • Food and refuse must be stored in a container designed to prevent access by bears, or counter-balanced at least 15 feet above the ground and 10 feet horizontally from a tree trunk (where containers are not required). 
  • Not passable for stock. 
  • Guiding in Hoover Wilderness is by Yosemite Mountaineering School only.
  • Hoover Wilderness regulations apply.  

USFS Webpage for: Lakes Canyon. 

https://www.fs.usda.gov/recarea/inyo/recreation/hiking/recarea/?recid=20648

488.name: Lakes Canyon (Non Quota)

493.description:
Upper Buttermilk trail is at the end of Buttermilk Road, historically known for shaking the milk cans on the farmer’s wagon so much it made buttermilk. The end of the road to Upper Buttermilk is still a rugged, high clearance dirt road.

Upper Buttermilk trail ends at Langley Reservoir, wedged between the foot of Mt. Humphreys and Basin Mountain.

Download map for trail names in this area.

https://www.fs.usda.gov/Internet/FSE_DOCUMENTS/stelprdb5337632.pdf

description_map.need_to_know:
Upper Buttermilk Area:  

This trail does not connect to the John Muir Trail.

  • No campfires above 10,000 ft. 
  • Food and refuse must be stored in a container designed to prevent access by bears, or counter-balanced at least 15 feet above the ground and 10 feet horizontally from a tree trunk (where containers are not required) 
  • John Muir Wilderness regulations apply  

USFS Webpage for: Upper Buttermilk. 

https://www.fs.usda.gov/recarea/inyo/recreation/hiking/recarea/?recid=37196

493.name: Upper Buttermilk

494.description:
Starting from Mosquito Flat at the end of Rock Creek Road, Mono Pass trail quickly separates from the trail into Little Lakes Valley. Follow the trail past Ruby Lake to reach Mono Pass (12,040 ft.) and descend along Mono Creek. Side trails go to Pioneer Basin and the Recesses. Mono Creek trail eventually connects with the John Muir Trail near Quail Meadows and Lake Thomas A Edison.

Another Mono Pass is on the border of Yosemite National Park. Search for Bloody Canyon trail on the Inyo National Forest side or Parker Pass trail from Yosemite.

Mono Pass trail includes Ruby Lake, but does not include other parts of Little Lakes Valley.

Download map for trail names in this area.

https://www.fs.usda.gov/Internet/FSE_DOCUMENTS/stelprdb5337631.pdf

description_map.need_to_know:
Mono Pass Area: 

Permit includes Ruby Lake but does not include other parts of Little Lakes Valley.

Backpackers starting on this trail may camp at the trailhead the night before their trip (10 walk in sites).  

  • No campfires above 10,000 ft. 
  • Food and refuse must be stored in a container designed to prevent access by bears if camping between the trail head and Mono Pass. There are not suitable trees to hang food beyond the pass as counter-balance must be at least 15 feet above the ground and 10 feet horizontally from a tree trunk. 
  • Trips going into Little Lakes Valley are a different permit. 
  • John Muir Wilderness regulations apply.  

USFS Webpage for: Mono Pass. 

https://www.fs.usda.gov/recarea/inyo/recreation/hiking/recarea/?recid=20406

494.name: Mono Pass

495.description:
Big Pine North Fork trail goes to the popular First through Seventh Lakes north of Temple Crag and Mount Sill. The hike starts across sunny sage and manzanita covered slopes above First Falls to enter the wilderness boundary near Second Falls. As the trail climbs past the chain of Big Pine Lakes you may see the effects of past glacial activity, such as glacier polish and erratics, those oddly balanced boulders left standing on the polished granite as the glacier melted.

A side trail to Black Lake offers views of Palisade Glacier and the Sierra Crest before looping back to the main trail near Fourth Lake.

Download map for trail names in this area.

description_map.need_to_know:
Big Pine North Fork Area:

No camping from trailhead to ¼ mile past wilderness boundary near Second Falls.

  • No campfires.

  • Food and refuse must be stored in a container designed to prevent access by bears, or counter-balanced at least 15 feet above the ground and 10 feet horizontally from a tree trunk (where containers are not required).

  • This permit does not include South Fork or Baker Lake.

  • John Muir Wilderness regulations apply.

  • Sequoia and Kings Canyon wilderness regulations apply if entering the park.(includes no pets; Dusy Basin has off trail group size eight with a two night camp limit; no night box permit pickup)

USFS Webpage for: Big Creek North Fork.

495.name: Big Pine Creek North Fork

4951.description: Big Pine North Fork trail goes to the popular First through Seventh Lakes up the canyon north of Mount Sill. This trail also offers views of Temple Crag and the Palisade Glacier. The hike begins at First Falls in the shade of Jeffrey pine and aspen and quickly climbs across sage and manzanita covered slopes to enter the wilderness boundary near Second Falls. As the trail climbs past the chain of Big Pine Lakes there are many opportunities to observe the effects of glacial activity, such as cirques, glaciated granite and glacial erratic. A side trail to Black Lake offers views of glaciers and the Sierra Crest before rejoining the main trail near Fourth Lake.
4951.name: Big Pine Creek North Fork (Pack Outfit)

4952.description: Big Pine North Fork trail goes to the popular First through Seventh Lakes up the canyon north of Mount Sill. This trail also offers views of Temple Crag and the Palisade Glacier. The hike begins at First Falls in the shade of Jeffrey pine and aspen and quickly climbs across sage and manzanita covered slopes to enter the wilderness boundary near Second Falls. As the trail climbs past the chain of Big Pine Lakes there are many opportunities to observe the effects of glacial activity, such as cirques, glaciated granite and glacial erratic. A side trail to Black Lake offers views of glaciers and the Sierra Crest before rejoining the main trail near Fourth Lake.
4952.name: Big Pine Creek North Fork (Outfitter)

497.description:
Starting from North Lake Campground, the Lamarck Lakes trail immediately splits away from the Piute Pass trail. Initially the trail is sheltered by a grove of aspen and pine. A steady climb soon leads to open views of Mount Emerson and the red cliffs of Piute Crags. Lakes are terraced up the canyon in a series of glacier carved granite benches. The trail ends at Upper Lamarck Lake. Rugged terrain beyond Upper Lamarck Lakes is predominately steep talus and snow fields that rest at the foot of Mount Lamarck.

Lamarck Lakes trail does not include the North Fork of Bishop Creek or Piute Pass.

Download map for trail names in this area.

https://www.fs.usda.gov/Internet/FSE_DOCUMENTS/stelprdb5337633.pdf

description_map.need_to_know:
Lamarck Lakes Area: 

Not recommended for stock above Lamarck Lake.  

  • No campfires above Grass Lake to Sierra Crest. 
  • Food and refuse must be stored in a container designed to prevent access by bears, or counter-balanced at least 15 feet above the ground and 10 feet horizontally from a tree trunk (where containers are not required). Trees are not tall enough to hang food at the upper lakes. 
  • John Muir Wilderness regulations apply. 
  • Sequoia and Kings Canyon wilderness regulations apply if entering the National Park (including no pets; no bear spray; group size limit 8 for Lamarck Col, Darwin Canyon)  

USFS Webpage for: Lamarck Lakes. 

https://www.fs.usda.gov/recarea/inyo/recreation/hiking/recarea/?recid=20368

497.name: Lamarck Lakes

498.description:
This short trail to a high meadow enters the Hoover Wilderness north of Hwy 120, east of Ellery Lake. The trail follows the creek, Warren Fork, for 1.5 miles in the canyon between Tioga Peak and Lee Vining Peak.

Download map for trail names in this area.

https://www.fs.usda.gov/Internet/FSE_DOCUMENTS/stelprdb5337621.pdf

description_map.need_to_know:
Warren Fork Area:

Warren Fork is a non-quota trail. Book your trip about a week before your entry date to allow time to check in by email. 

  • Permit for Warren Fork is limited to Hoover Wilderness.
  • Food and refuse must be stored in a container designed to prevent access by bears, or counter-balanced at least 15 feet above the ground and 10 feet horizontally from a tree trunk (where containers are not required) 
  • Guiding in Hoover Wilderness is by Yosemite Mountaineering School 
  • Hoover Wilderness regulations apply.  

USFS Webpage for: Warren Fork 

https://www.fs.usda.gov/recarea/inyo/recreation/hiking/recarea/?recid=20650

498.name: Warren Fork (Non Quota)

506.description:
Just east of Yosemite National Park, Saddlebag Lake is very popular for day hikes and fishing. A loop trail goes around Saddlebag Lake with trails extending into Hoover Wilderness and the 20 Lakes Basin. Go past Saddlebag Lake and beyond the north side of Greenstone Lake before selecting a campsite.

The area around Saddlebag Lake and the Harvey Monroe Hall Natural Research Area are day use only. The Hall Natural Research Area is used to study plants and animals at high elevation, so if you are day hiking in this area please take extra care to Leave No Trace.

Download map for trail names in this area (map includes Hall Natural Area)

https://www.fs.usda.gov/Internet/FSE_DOCUMENTS/stelprdb5337621.pdf

This non-quota trail gives unlimited entry to the 20 Lakes Basin. Book your trip about a week before your entry date to allow time to check in by email. 

  • No campfires in 20 Lakes Basin or Hall Natural Research Area.
  • Food and refuse must be stored in a container designed to prevent access by bears, or counter-balanced at least 15 feet above the ground and 10 feet horizontally from a tree trunk (where containers are not required) 
  • No camping at Wasco or Conness Lakes, or in Hall Natural Research Area.
  • Guiding in Hoover Wilderness is by Yosemite Mountaineering School only.
  • Hoover Wilderness regulations apply.  

USFS Webpage for: Saddlebag Lake
