506.name: Saddlebag Lake (Non Quota)

511.description:
Gibbs Lake trail climbs up pine covered slopes and along Gibbs Creek. This small lake is tucked in the canyon between Mount Dana and Mount Gibbs. The trail is not recommended for stock beyond the wilderness boundary. The trailhead at Upper Horse Meadows is located at the end of three miles of dirt road.

Download map for trail names in this area.

https://www.fs.usda.gov/Internet/FSE_DOCUMENTS/stelprdb5337622.pdf

description_map.need_to_know:
Gibbs Lake Area: 

This area does not connect to the John Muir Trail

  • This trail is not recommended for stock.  
  • No campfires above 10,000 ft. 
  • Food and refuse must be stored in a container designed to prevent access by bears, or counter-balanced at least 15 feet above the ground and 10 feet horizontally from a tree trunk (where containers are not required). 
  • Ansel Adams Wilderness regulations apply.  

USFS Webpage for: Gibbs Lake. 

https://www.fs.usda.gov/recarea/inyo/recreation/hiking/recarea/?recid=20654

511.name: Gibbs Lake

512.description:
North Fork of Lone Pine Creek trail includes the approach to the Mountaineers Route. The trail is steep and hard to follow as you climb up and scramble over the Ebersbacher Ledges to reach Boy Scout Lakes. Parts of the route cross granite slabs requiring route finding skills. The trail ends at Iceberg Lake, at an elevation of about 12,600 feet.

There is not a hiking trail to the summit, climbing routes above Iceberg Lake vary in technical difficulty (Mountaineers Route, East Face, East Buttress, or Mt Russell). Research the difficulty before attempting these routes.

Single day trip requires a Mt. Whitney Zone Day Use Permit.

Download map for trail names in this area.

https://www.fs.usda.gov/Internet/FSE_DOCUMENTS/stelprdb5337643.pdf

description_map.need_to_know:
North Fork of Lone Pine Creek Area:

All Mt. Whitney hikers are expected to pack-out their poop. Pack-out kits are provided. Disposal box for used kits is next to trailhead restroom.

Be Bear Aware!

  • Hikers, do not leave your pack or food unattended

  • Removed all food items from cars and secure in bear proof lockers

  • Put trash in bear proof trashcans at trailhead

  • On the trail you must secure food and refuse in containers designed to prevent access by bears, there are no trees in this canyon suitable to hang food

John Muir Wilderness regulations apply, including:

  • No campfires

  • Stock is not allowed

USFS Webpage for: North Fork of Lone Pine Creek.

https://www.fs.usda.gov/recarea/inyo/recreation/hiking/recarea/?recid=20808

512.name: North Fork of Lone Pine Creek

516.description:
Exiting via Trail Crest allows you the option to hike to the summit of Mt Whitney and camp along the Mt Whitney trail as you finish your trip.

All Mt. Whitney visitors are expected to pack-out their solid human waste. Pack-out kits are provided with wilderness permits.

Trail Crest is approximately 13,600 ft. in elevation and two miles from the summit of Mt. Whitney, where the Mt. Whitney trail crosses the crest of the Sierra Nevada to join the John Muir Trail in Sequoia National Park.

Trail Crest exit quota applies to visitors who descend the Mt. Whitney trail to Whitney Portal Road. Hikers that begin their trip in another park or forest are exempt from this exit quota, the permit issued by your entry location is valid to visit Mt Whitney.

description_map.need_to_know:
Mt Whitney Area:

All Mt. Whitney visitors are expected to pack-out their solid human waste. Pack-out kits are provided. Disposal box for used kits is next to trailhead restroom.

  • Special approval is required for commercial use. Stock is not allowed Trail Crest to Whitney Portal

  • No Campfires.

Be Bear Aware! There is a high level of bear activity in the Mt. Whitney area.

  • All food and scented items must be removed from vehicles and stored in the bear proof lockers located in parking areas. Put trash in bear proof trashcans at the trailhead

  • Use bear-proof containers to store all food and refuse, there are no trees in this canyon suitable to hang food.

USFS Webpage: Mt Whitney

https://www.fs.usda.gov/main/inyo/passes-permits/recreation#Whitney

516.name: Mt. Whitney (Trail Crest Exit)

517.description:
This route was used to cross the Sierras before wagon roads were built and is named for the injuries to stock that made this rugged crossing. The trail starts by climbing over a ridge to view Walker Lake and goes up Bloody Canyon past Lower and Upper Sardine Lakes.

Bloody Canyon trail crosses Mono Pass at the head of the canyon and enters Yosemite National Park where it joins the Parker Pass trail. You can descend to end your trip at Dana Meadows in Yosemite, or continue on the Parker Pass trail south along the Sierra Crest toward Koip Peak Pass and the Kuna Crest.

Download map for trail names in this area.

description_map.need_to_know:
Bloody Canyon Area:

Special approval is required for commercial use. Stock is not recommended.

  • No campfires at Lower Sardine Lake or anywhere above 10,000 ft.

  • Food and refuse must be stored in a container designed to prevent access by bears, or counter-balanced at least 15 feet above the ground and 10 feet horizontally from a tree trunk (where containers are not required).

  • This area is near Bighorn Sheep habitat. Use of pack goats is not advised in order to protect the health of the wild sheep.

  • Yosemite wilderness regulations apply when visiting the National Park. (includes no pets; no camping from Dana Meadow to Koip Peak Pass, Inyo NF permit ends at Dana Meadow)

USFS Webpage for: Bloody Canyon.

517.name: Bloody Canyon

518.description:
Located in the northeastern part of the South Sierra Wilderness the Olancha Pass trail starts at Sage Flat trailhead at elevation 5,790 feet. This trail begins in canyon live oak woodland and winds steeply up the Eastern Sierra escarpment to Olancha Pass (9,220 ft) and Summit Meadow in a lodgepole pine forest. The Olancha Pass trail junctions with the Pacific Crest Trail and the trail to Monache Meadow.

Download map for trail names in this area.

https://www.fs.usda.gov/Internet/FSE_DOCUMENTS/stelprdb5337645.pdf

description_map.need_to_know:
Olancha Pass Area: 

This non-quota trail gives unlimited entry to South Sierra Wilderness. If your trip will continue north of Olancha Peak into Golden Trout Wilderness, contact Inyo National Forest for information about how to reserve a permit.  

  • Food and refuse must be stored in a container designed to prevent access by bears, or counter-balanced at least 15 feet above the ground and 10 feet horizontally from a tree trunk (where containers are not required) 
  • If your travel plan will stay within the South Sierra Wilderness no permit is required (carry a California Campfire Permit for stove use)
  • South Sierra Wilderness regulations apply  

USFS Webpage for: Olancha Pass 

https://www.fs.usda.gov/recarea/inyo/recreation/hiking/recarea/?recid=20916

518.name: Olancha Pass (Non Quota)

519.description:
This short trail begins in the sage and rocky environment of the Owens Valley in the shadow of Lone Pine Peak and Mount Corcoran. Shortly beyond the wilderness boundary the trail becomes a faint game trail.

Tuttle Creek trail goes approximately one mile to the forks of Tuttle Creek and the site of an abandoned stone building at an altitude of 7,600 feet.

The final portion of the dirt road to the trailhead is often not passable, adding up to one mile of walking on the road.

Download map for trail names in this area.

https://www.fs.usda.gov/Internet/FSE_DOCUMENTS/stelprdb5337643.pdf

description_map.need_to_know:
Tuttle Creek Area: 

Permit for Tuttle Creek does not include John Muir Trail.

  • Special approval is required for commercial guide use. The trail is not recommended for stock.  
  • No campfires above 10,400 ft. 
  • Food and refuse must be stored in a container designed to prevent access by bears, or counter-balanced at least 15 feet above the ground and 10 feet horizontally from a tree trunk (where containers are not required) 
  • John Muir Wilderness regulations apply 
  • Sequoia and Kings Canyon wilderness regulations apply if entering the park (includes no pets, no bear spray, group size limit eight for Miter Basin/ Mt Langley areas)

USFS Webpage for: Tuttle Creek. 

https://www.fs.usda.gov/recarea/inyo/recreation/hiking/recarea/?recid=20724

519.name: Tuttle Creek

520.description:
Cottonwood Lakes are home to California's state fish, the golden trout. Located near Horseshoe Meadows, the Cottonwood Lakes Basin has many pristine lakes and creeks located between Mount Langley and Cirque Peak. Side trails go to Muir Lake, Hidden Lake, South Fork Lakes, Cirque Lake, Long Lake and High Lake. Climbing over New Army Pass crosses into the southern portion of Sequoia National Park. 

Anglers should note only artificial lures may be used, limit of 2 trout. For Lakes 1 – 4 and their tributaries the season is open Sept. 1 through Nov 30 with minimum size limit of 14 inches. Other lakes in the basin are open all year. 

Download map for trail names in this area. 

https://www.fs.usda.gov/Internet/FSE_DOCUMENTS/stelprdb5337644.pdf

description_map.need_to_know:
Cottonwood Lakes Area:

Permit for Cottonwood Lakes may continue over Army Pass and continue on the Pacific Crest Trail. 

  • No campfires in the Cottonwood Lakes Basin or above 10,400 ft. 
  • Bear containers are required for storage of food and trash. 
  • 2021 change in special fishing regulations in this area.
  • Not recommended for stock between Lakes 1 and 2; or South Fork of Cottonwood Creek. 
  • John Muir Wilderness regulations apply. 
  • Sequoia and Kings Canyon wilderness regulations apply if entering the National Park (includes no pets; group size limit eight to hike to Mt Langley; three night limit at Soldier Lakes).  

USFS Webpage for: Cottonwood Lakes. 

https://www.fs.usda.gov/recarea/inyo/recreation/hiking/recarea/?recid=20896
